2007-07-10 19:31  bernlohr

	* eventio_addon/io_histogram.c (1.11), eventio_addon/io_histogram.h
	  (1.5), hess/io_hess.h (1.30): Get rid of a couple of more GCC 4.2
	  warnings.

2007-07-10 13:55  bernlohr

	* common/current.c (1.6), common/current.h (1.3), common/hconfig.c
	  (1.11), common/hconfig.h (1.4), common/histogram.c (1.11),
	  common/histogram.h (1.9), common/history.h (1.3),
	  common/warning.c (1.5), common/warning.h (1.2), corsika/mc_tel.h
	  (1.6), eventio_addon/io_histogram.c (1.10),
	  eventio_addon/io_histogram.h (1.4), eventio_addon/io_history.c
	  (1.4), eventio_addon/io_history.h (1.3), eventio_basic/EventIO.cc
	  (1.21), eventio_basic/EventIO.hh (1.27), eventio_basic/TestIO.cc
	  (1.17), eventio_basic/eventio.c (1.18), eventio_basic/io_basic.h
	  (1.10), eventio_basic/listio.c (1.9), eventio_basic/testio.c
	  (1.14), hbook/cvt2.c (1.15), hbook/tohbook.c (1.5),
	  hbook/tohbook.h (1.4), hess/io_hess.c (1.28), hess/io_hess.h
	  (1.29), root/cvt3.cc (1.12): Here comes a rather big set of
	  changes:

	  - This includes the first change to the eventio data format for
	  more than a decade. It provides an optional extension field to
	  item headers of which so far 12 bits have been assigned for
	  extending the length field from 30 bits (1 GByte) to 42 bits (4
	  TByte) on 64-bit systems. On 32-bit systems no I/O blocks of more
	  than 2 GByte can be handled. By default, all data is written in
	  the old format, without extension field. Therefore, all existing
	  software should continue to work as before and writing data that
	  can be read with older eventio versions. Automatic insertion of
	  the extension field, which is possible though extremely
	  inefficient, is not implemented yet. To take advantage of the
	  extension field, one has to set the 'extended' flag in the I/O
	  buffer once or use the put_item_begin_with_flags function with
	  the corresponding flag set for each item that might exceed the
	  GByte barrier.

	  - Another (minor) change to the data format is setting aside a
	  previously reserved bit in the type/version field for a
	  user-controlled flag bit.  If data with this flag set is read by
	  older software, the flag will simply be ignored. Again, by
	  default, everything is written as it used to be.

	  - The testio and TestIO programs have been extended for a more
	  complete coverage of the eventio functionality. Both of them can
	  write and read their data in the old format as well as the
	  extended format.

	  - The C++ interface has been extended to cover the same level of
	  functionality as the C interface, without need to call the C
	  functions directly.

	  - The remaining support for pre-ANSI-C compilers has been
	  dropped.

2007-06-15 12:56  bernlohr

	* common/initial.h (1.9): Avoid warnings about redefined
	  __STDC_LIMIT_MACROS if defined elsewhere.

2007-06-15 12:53  bernlohr

